(41, 2, 15, 40, 9, 10, 11, 'many publicans and sinners sat also together', 'Eating with Sinners', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus dining with publicans and sinners, highlighting his association with those marginalized by society. The Pharisees'' question in Matthew reflects their concern over this behavior, which is also noted in Mark.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 15, 42, 5, 29, 30, 'publicans and sinners sat also together', 'Connection of Feasting with Sinners', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus dining with publicans and sinners, highlighting the social context of his ministry. The murmuring of the Pharisees in Luke reflects the same concern present in Mark about Jesus'' associations.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 15, 40, 21, 31, 32, 'publicans and sinners', 'Connection of Publicans and Sinners', 'Both passages emphasize the inclusion of publicans, highlighting their acceptance in God''s kingdom. This connection illustrates the contrast between those deemed righteous and those considered sinners who believe.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 15, 42, 6, 17, 17, NULL, 'Gathering of Followers', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of people around Jesus. In Mark, publicans and sinners follow him, while in Luke, a multitude comes to hear and be healed by him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 16, 42, 18, 11, 11, 'publicans and sinners', 'Pharisees and Publicans Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the Pharisees'' disdain for publicans. In Mark, the Pharisees question Jesus about eating with publicans, while in Luke, a Pharisee expresses his superiority over a publican in prayer.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 16, 42, 19, 7, 7, 'eateth and drinketh with publicans and sinners', 'Jesus Dining with Sinners', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' association with sinners, highlighting the criticism he faced for eating with them. The murmuring in Luke reflects the same concern expressed by the Pharisees in Mark.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 16, 23, 65, 5, 5, NULL, 'Holiness and Social Exclusion', 'This connection highlights the theme of social exclusion based on perceived holiness. Both passages emphasize the attitudes of those who consider themselves ''holier than thou'' and their disdain for those deemed ''publicans and sinners.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 16, 44, 23, 9, 9, 'scribes and Pharisees', 'Scribes and Pharisees'' Reactions', 'This connection highlights the ongoing scrutiny of Jesus by the scribes and Pharisees, as seen in both passages. In Mark, they question his association with sinners, while in Acts, some Pharisees defend Paul, suggesting a complex relationship with authority and belief.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 16, 46, 2, 15, 15, NULL, 'Judgment and Spiritual Insight', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment in both passages. In Mark, the Pharisees question Jesus'' associations, while in Corinthians, the spiritual person judges all things, indicating a deeper understanding beyond societal norms.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 16, 40, 9, 11, 11, NULL, 'Connection of Pharisees'' Question', 'Both passages emphasize the Pharisees'' inquiry about Jesus eating with publicans and sinners. This connection highlights a shared concern regarding Jesus'' associations.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 16, 40, 18, 17, 17, 'publicans and sinners', 'Connection of Publicans and Sinners', 'Both passages emphasize the role of publicans in the context of social and religious exclusion. In Mark, publicans and sinners are associated with Jesus'' acceptance, while in Matthew, publicans are mentioned in the context of being treated as outsiders.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 17, 40, 9, 12, 13, 'I came not to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance', 'Connection of Healing and Mercy', 'Both passages emphasize the need for a physician for the sick and highlight Jesus'' mission to call sinners to repentance. The phrase ''I came not to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance'' appears in both, reinforcing the theme of mercy over sacrifice.', 'theme', 0.5449999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 17, 42, 15, 7, 7, 'sinners to repentance', 'Repentance and Joy in Heaven', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of repentance for sinners. Mark highlights Jesus'' mission to call sinners, while Luke illustrates the joy in heaven over a sinner''s repentance.', 'theme', 0.5449999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 17, 42, 5, 31, 32, 'I came not to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance.', 'Connection of Healing and Repentance', 'Both passages emphasize the need for a physician for the sick and the call for sinners to repentance. This connection highlights Jesus'' mission to reach those in need rather than the righteous.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 17, 54, 1, 15, 16, 'I came not to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance', 'Connection of Jesus'' Mission', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' purpose in coming to save sinners. Mark highlights that he calls sinners to repentance, while 1 Timothy states that he came to save sinners, illustrating a consistent theme of mercy and redemption.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 17, 56, 3, 3, 7, 'I came not to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance', 'Call to Repentance and Mercy', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' mission to call sinners to repentance, as seen in Mark 2:17, and the acknowledgment of human folly and need for mercy in Titus 3:3. Both passages emphasize the necessity of divine intervention for those who are spiritually ''sick'' and in need of salvation.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 17, 45, 5, 6, 8, 'sinners to repentance', 'Connection of Sinners and Christ''s Sacrifice', 'Both passages emphasize the need for sinners and the role of Christ in their redemption. Mark highlights Jesus'' mission to call sinners, while Romans illustrates His sacrificial love for the ungodly.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 17, 23, 55, 7, 7, 'I came not to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance', 'Call to Repentance', 'This connection highlights the theme of calling sinners to repentance. Both passages emphasize the need for the wicked to forsake their ways and return to God for mercy.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 18, 40, 6, 18, 18, 'fast, but thy disciples fast not', 'Fasting and Divine Reward', 'This connection highlights the theme of fasting and its purpose. Both passages address the practice of fasting, with Mark questioning the public nature of fasting and Matthew emphasizing fasting in secret for divine reward.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 18, 40, 9, 14, 17, 'Why do the disciples of John', 'Fasting and Newness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the question of fasting in relation to Jesus'' presence. They highlight the contrast between the old practices of fasting and the new reality brought by Jesus, symbolized by the bridegroom and new wine.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 18, 42, 18, 12, 12, 'fast, but thy disciples fast not', 'Fasting Practices in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the practice of fasting as a significant aspect of religious observance. Both passages emphasize the contrast between the fasting of the Pharisees and John''s disciples and the lack of fasting by Jesus'' disciples.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 18, 42, 5, 33, 39, NULL, 'Fasting and Newness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the question of fasting among Jesus'' disciples compared to others. They highlight the contrast between old practices and the new approach Jesus represents.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 18, 45, 10, 3, 3, NULL, 'Righteousness and Fasting Connection', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the righteousness sought by the Pharisees and the disciples of John, who fast, and the righteousness of God that is not recognized by those establishing their own. Both passages emphasize the theme of seeking true righteousness versus human traditions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 19, 40, 25, 1, 10, 'bridegroom', 'Connection of Bridegroom Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the figure of the bridegroom, symbolizing presence and readiness. In Mark, the bridegroom''s presence signifies joy, while in Matthew, the bridegroom''s arrival tests the preparedness of the virgins.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 19, 1, 29, 22, 22, 'bridegroom is with them', 'Feasting and Celebration', 'This connection highlights the theme of celebration during significant events. In Mark, the presence of the bridegroom signifies a time of joy, paralleling the feast in Genesis, which is a communal celebration.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 19, 7, 14, 10, 11, 'bridegroom is with them', 'Feasting and Celebration Context', 'This connection highlights the theme of celebration in both passages. In Mark, the presence of the bridegroom signifies a time of joy, while in Judges, the feast represents a communal celebration among Samson and his companions.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 19, 19, 45, 14, 14, 'bridegroom is with them', 'Connection of Bridegroom and Bride', 'This connection highlights the imagery of a wedding celebration, where the presence of the bridegroom signifies joy and festivity, contrasting with the practice of fasting. Both passages emphasize the significance of the bride and bridegroom relationship, illustrating a theme of celebration and companionship.', 'theme', 0.293, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 19, 22, 6, 8, 8, 'bridegroom is with them', 'Connection of Bridegroom Imagery', 'This connection highlights the imagery of a bridegroom in both passages. In Mark, Jesus refers to himself as the bridegroom, while Song of Solomon speaks of a multitude of brides, emphasizing the theme of love and celebration.', 'theme', 0.293, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 20, 42, 17, 22, 22, 'the days will come', 'Connection of Future Longing', 'Both passages emphasize a future time when the disciples will experience a longing for the presence of Jesus. In Mark, the absence of the bridegroom leads to fasting, while in Luke, the disciples desire to see the days of the Son of man.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 2, 20, 66, 21, 9, 9, 'bridegroom shall be taken away', 'Connection of Bridegroom and Bride', 'This connection highlights the theme of the bridegroom''s absence in Mark, which leads to fasting, and the eventual revelation of the bride in Revelation. Both passages emphasize the relationship between the bridegroom and the bride, symbolizing a deeper union in the eschatological context.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
